1
00:02:53,326 --> 00:02:55,894
Her name was Odessa Cotter.

2
00:02:55,896 --> 00:02:58,163
I called her Dessie.

3
00:02:58,165 --> 00:03:02,391
As best as anyone knows, she was
the first woman to rock me to sleep.

4
00:03:03,203 --> 00:03:08,024
There wasn't anything
extraordinary about her, but,

5
00:03:08,280 --> 00:03:10,398
I guess there's
always somethin'...

6
00:03:10,412 --> 00:03:14,076
extraordinary about
someone who changes...

7
00:03:14,111 --> 00:03:16,820
and then changes
those around her.

8
00:03:18,083 --> 00:03:19,562
That's me.

9
00:03:19,651 --> 00:03:22,490
- Morning, Mary Catherine.
- I was only seven years old.

10
00:03:24,959 --> 00:03:27,161
Excuse me, Odessa.
I didn't mean to run you down.

11
00:03:27,163 --> 00:03:29,777
- Is that a car or a boat?
- It's a piece of sausage.

12
00:03:29,812 --> 00:03:32,199
- You tell her, sweetness. - Odessa,
we're having a cocktail party tonight,

13
00:03:32,201 --> 00:03:34,334
so I'm sending you to Oak Park
with Mary Catherine...

14
00:03:34,336 --> 00:03:36,773
- just as soon as Claudia gets here.
- Yes, ma'am.

15
00:03:37,906 --> 00:03:39,339
Honey.

16
00:03:41,142 --> 00:03:45,280
- Look what you did. Boop. Gotcha.
- Has anyone seen my racket?

17
00:03:45,314 --> 00:03:47,377
- Oh, I know where it is.
- Bye-bye.

18
00:03:47,412 --> 00:03:49,150
- Bye.
- Oh, my clubs.

19
00:03:49,152 --> 00:03:53,338
- I wanna cut something.
- Not today, young lady.

20
00:03:53,373 --> 00:03:56,124
Ah, your hands are sticky.

21
00:03:56,126 --> 00:03:59,823
- Oh, she's been beside herself for weeks.
- That's 'cause you never discipline her.

22
00:04:00,263 --> 00:04:02,263
- Where are you going?
- One guess, Sherlock.

23
00:04:02,265 --> 00:04:04,399
- Trey and I are playing at the club.
- Oh, well.

24
00:04:04,401 --> 00:04:06,824
- I wanna see Trey's car.
- Here are my clubs, honey.

25
00:04:06,859 --> 00:04:09,299
- If you can get 'em to the pro shop.
- I'm givin' a party tonight.

26
00:04:09,334 --> 00:04:10,773
Catch Sara.
She's on her way to the club.

27
00:04:10,775 --> 00:04:13,175
I can't play with the grips like that.
Thank you, sweetie.

28
00:04:13,177 --> 00:04:15,778
- I'll see you at 6:00, huh?
- See you at 6:00.

29
00:04:48,546 --> 00:04:51,234
Odessa, just have 'em
waitin' out here at 3:00.

30
00:04:51,269 --> 00:04:54,454
- I should be back from the beauty parlor
and Junior League by then. - Yes, ma'am.

31
00:04:54,854 --> 00:04:56,970
- You be good, Mary Catherine.
- I will.

32
00:04:58,157 --> 00:04:59,924
Bye!

33
00:05:05,564 --> 00:05:07,365
Feel a tickle comin'.

34
00:05:12,561 --> 00:05:14,135
Go on.

35
00:05:16,943 --> 00:05:19,278
Y'all come on now.
It's time to eat.

36
00:05:46,644 --> 00:05:48,292
Hey!

37
00:05:54,652 --> 00:05:56,148
Hey!

38
00:06:00,922 --> 00:06:02,623
What you doin' here?

39
00:06:05,293 --> 00:06:08,529
Can't you hear me, nigger?
What are you doin' in this park?

40
00:06:08,892 --> 00:06:10,892
Just takin' care of
Mrs. Thompson's...

41
00:06:11,048 --> 00:06:13,493
Don't give me any of
that mealy-mouthed crap!

42
00:06:13,971 --> 00:06:16,151
Now, this park
is whites only,

43
00:06:16,186 --> 00:06:19,836
and that means niggers like you best
answer with "yes, sir" when spoken to.

44
00:06:19,871 --> 00:06:22,316
I don't care who
you're takin' care of!

45
00:06:25,915 --> 00:06:28,059
You don't understand
nothin', do you?

46
00:06:30,286 --> 00:06:33,588
Go on. Get your stuff together
and get on out of here!

47
00:06:40,030 --> 00:06:42,498
Come on, Mary Catherine.
Get your friends. We got to go.

48
00:06:46,370 --> 00:06:49,906
I never heard such
nonsense in all my life.

49
00:06:49,908 --> 00:06:51,937
Let me just see about this.

50
00:07:12,263 --> 00:07:15,098
Hello. Could I speak to
Commissioner Sellers, please?

51
00:07:16,134 --> 00:07:18,461
Mrs. Norman Thompson.

52
00:07:20,139 --> 00:07:22,240
Well, would you tell
Clyde Sellers...

53
00:07:22,242 --> 00:07:26,044
that one of his policemen threw my
nine-year-old daughter out of Oak Park?

54
00:07:26,046 --> 00:07:28,012
He knows who I am.

55
00:07:35,621 --> 00:07:39,688
- I really appreciate you coming by
this afternoon. - Oh, not at all, ma'am.

56
00:07:39,916 --> 00:07:42,425
- I'm just sorry about the
misunderstanding. - Thank you.

57
00:07:47,267 --> 00:07:51,280
Mrs. Cotter, I would like to apologize
on behalf of myself,

58
00:07:51,498 --> 00:07:52,929
the police department,

59
00:07:53,095 --> 00:07:56,130
and the city of Montgomery for
what happened today in Oak Park.

60
00:07:57,444 --> 00:08:00,315
Hope y'all come back to
the park someday soon.

61
00:08:03,050 --> 00:08:05,518
I hope I didn't cause you too
much trouble, Mrs. Thompson.

62
00:08:05,520 --> 00:08:08,588
I'm sorry if I embarrassed your
maid in front of the children.

63
00:08:09,207 --> 00:08:10,166
Thank you.

64
00:08:10,554 --> 00:08:13,293
- Thank you very much.
- You're welcome, ma'am.

65
00:08:13,328 --> 00:08:15,463
I regret that this happened
in the first place.

66
00:08:15,498 --> 00:08:18,296
- Well, send the commissioner my best.
- I will, ma'am.

67
00:08:19,735 --> 00:08:21,569
Shh.

68
00:08:26,100 --> 00:08:27,658
Y'all come on inside.

69
00:08:42,387 --> 00:08:45,172
Alabama's got a small line,
but they're agile.

70
00:08:45,611 --> 00:08:47,502
Oh, my God.

71
00:08:48,182 --> 00:08:50,218
How's my little Boo-Boo?

72
00:08:50,266 --> 00:08:52,201
Tunker's here.

73
00:08:52,736 --> 00:08:54,603
Tunker.
Tunker, welcome.

74
00:08:54,605 --> 00:08:57,180
- Hello, Norman.
- I'm glad you could make it.

75
00:08:57,215 --> 00:08:59,474
Yeah.
It's a nice-lookin' party here.

76
00:08:59,476 --> 00:09:01,949
- Yeah. We try. We do.
- Hello, Miriam.

77
00:09:03,752 --> 00:09:06,138
- That a bartender?
- Yeah.

78
00:09:06,173 --> 00:09:09,634
- Does I has to tip him?
- Well, being you're my baby brother,

79
00:09:09,669 --> 00:09:12,305
why don't we just say that the
drinks are two bucks, all inclusive.

80
00:09:12,340 --> 00:09:15,491
Thanks. Thanks. Hey, y'all lucky
to get a bartender at all.

81
00:09:15,493 --> 00:09:18,594
The niggers are all
movin' to Philadelphia.

82
00:09:19,190 --> 00:09:22,375
- Why's that? - 'Cause they hear
there ain't no work in Philadelphia.

83
00:09:26,416 --> 00:09:29,603
- I don't get it.
- Honey, you never get jokes.

84
00:09:29,896 --> 00:09:31,513
What?

85
00:09:35,560 --> 00:09:37,994
Tunker, don't be so loud
this close to the bar.

86
00:09:38,029 --> 00:09:40,964
- Oh, he didn't hear me.
- You better be careful.

87
00:09:40,999 --> 00:09:42,820
She'll have you out there
apologizin' to him.

88
00:09:45,320 --> 00:09:46,879
What's this?

89
00:09:46,914 --> 00:09:50,410
- Nothin'. It was just somethin' stupid,
that's all. - I'd like to know.

90
00:09:50,840 --> 00:09:52,716
Go on.
Tell him.

91
00:09:53,112 --> 00:09:55,942
Some young policeman
threw our maid out of Oak Park.

92
00:09:55,977 --> 00:09:59,262
Mary Catherine and her friends were
right there, and he was extremely rude.

93
00:09:59,297 --> 00:10:02,397
So I called up Clyde Sellers,
and he had him come out and apologize.

94
00:10:03,920 --> 00:10:07,399
Well, what were you doing sending
your maid into that park anyway?

95
00:10:07,498 --> 00:10:09,345
Tunker, she was takin'
care of the children.

96
00:10:09,380 --> 00:10:12,765
But you shouldn't have the poor fellow come
out and apologize to a nigger, Miriam.

97
00:10:12,767 --> 00:10:14,868
That's plain old wrong.

98
00:10:14,870 --> 00:10:17,705
Tunker, it's not like she was parading
her own children around the park,

99
00:10:17,707 --> 00:10:19,239
for heaven's sakes.

100
00:10:19,241 --> 00:10:21,275
And you know,
I did grow up with a maid,

101
00:10:21,277 --> 00:10:24,311
and I've had them all my life, and I know
what's right and I know what's wrong.

102
00:10:24,313 --> 00:10:27,683
And I will not have my judgment impugned
by some wet-behind-the-ears patrolman...

103
00:10:27,685 --> 00:10:29,118
or by you.

104
00:10:29,120 --> 00:10:30,720
Excuse me.

105
00:10:33,056 --> 00:10:35,392
Oh, hi, Liz.
How are you?

106
00:10:35,394 --> 00:10:38,933
She's a hellcat, Norman.
I always thought so.

107
00:10:41,699 --> 00:10:43,934
<i>Mr. Sandman</i>

108
00:10:43,936 --> 00:10:46,770
<i>Bring me a dream</i>

109
00:10:46,772 --> 00:10:49,641
<i>Make him the cutest
that I've ever seen</i>

110
00:10:49,643 --> 00:10:52,076
My world was a bubble
when I was seven.

111
00:10:52,078 --> 00:10:54,213
Wars could have been going on
outside our front door,

112
00:10:54,215 --> 00:10:55,914
and I would have been
all the happier.

113
00:10:55,916 --> 00:10:57,816
Thank you, darling.

114
00:11:01,854 --> 00:11:05,091
- In a way, a war was about
to start in Montgomery. - Hey!

115
00:11:05,093 --> 00:11:07,160
- A war of wills...
- Give that back!

116
00:11:07,162 --> 00:11:09,897
in the cradle of
the Confederacy.

117
00:11:09,899 --> 00:11:13,864
- It began on a crisp December day.
- Hey!

118
00:11:14,238 --> 00:11:16,138
Give it back!

119
00:11:18,889 --> 00:11:20,450
Give it back.

120
00:11:25,224 --> 00:11:26,511
Give it back!

121
00:11:27,382 --> 00:11:29,718
Mama!
Where you at?

122
00:11:29,720 --> 00:11:32,221
What you comin' in here
screamin' like a banshee about?

123
00:11:32,223 --> 00:11:34,992
A lady gave these out
to everybody after school.

124
00:11:34,994 --> 00:11:37,761
I'll read it to you.

125
00:11:37,763 --> 00:11:40,931
"This is for...

126
00:11:40,933 --> 00:11:43,333
Monday the"...

127
00:11:43,335 --> 00:11:46,271
Boy, you can't read. We're gonna
die of consumption waitin' for you.

128
00:11:46,273 --> 00:11:50,775
- Can so! Give it back! - Franklin, give
him the paper and let him read it.

129
00:11:52,244 --> 00:11:53,813
Watch it.

130
00:11:55,950 --> 00:11:59,251
"Another Negro woman has
been arrested and thrown in jail

131
00:11:59,253 --> 00:12:02,823
because she refused to get up
out of her seat on the bus...

132
00:12:02,825 --> 00:12:05,425
for a white person
to sit down.

133
00:12:05,427 --> 00:12:08,095
It is the second time
since the Colvin case...

134
00:12:08,097 --> 00:12:12,047
that a Negro woman has been
arrested for the same thing.

135
00:12:12,134 --> 00:12:14,203
This has to be stopped. "

136
00:12:14,205 --> 00:12:16,271
"We're therefore asking
every Negro...

137
00:12:16,273 --> 00:12:20,688
to stay off the buses Monday
in protest of the arrest and trial.

138
00:12:20,811 --> 00:12:25,207
Don't ride the buses to work,
to town, to school...

139
00:12:25,242 --> 00:12:26,949
or anywhere on Monday.

140
00:12:26,951 --> 00:12:29,219
You can afford to stay
out of school for one day,

141
00:12:29,221 --> 00:12:32,454
if you have no other
way to go except by bus.

142
00:12:32,456 --> 00:12:35,761
You can also afford to stay
out of town for one day.

143
00:12:35,763 --> 00:12:38,996
If you work,
take a cab or walk.

144
00:12:38,998 --> 00:12:41,433
- Please, children"...
- I heard about that last night.

145
00:12:41,435 --> 00:12:44,068
- That woman was Miss Parks.
- Rosa Parks?

146
00:12:44,070 --> 00:12:47,272
Yep. They had to bail her out
of jail for sittin' in the bus.

147
00:12:48,941 --> 00:12:51,977
- See, the problem is...
- I'll tell you what the problem is.

148
00:12:51,979 --> 00:12:55,114
I ain't never seen people get so
worked up over a piece of paper.

149
00:12:55,116 --> 00:12:57,016
- I think it's dumb.
- I think you're dumb!

150
00:12:57,018 --> 00:12:59,787
- Shut up, Franklin.
- I bet nobody rides the bus.

151
00:12:59,789 --> 00:13:03,514
- Franklin, sit up.
- Well, if that don't get all.

152
00:13:03,977 --> 00:13:07,561
Here we are without a car,
and somebody tellin' us not to ride the bus?

153
00:13:07,563 --> 00:13:10,198
Theodore and Franklin ready
to follow along like lap dogs.

154
00:13:10,200 --> 00:13:12,801
If that ain't cuttin' your
nose off to spite your face.

155
00:13:12,803 --> 00:13:16,906
She's mad 'cause she ride the bus
out to Newtown on Saturday,

156
00:13:16,908 --> 00:13:20,251
- to see that boy she think like her.
- Shut up.

157
00:13:29,887 --> 00:13:32,925
I'm tired of hangin' my head
in the shadow of crackers.

158
00:13:34,525 --> 00:13:37,028
I wanna ride at the
front of the bus.

159
00:13:39,464 --> 00:13:44,162
Lord, we thank you for this
food we're about to receive.

160
00:13:45,605 --> 00:13:49,007
Watch over our
souls tonight...

161
00:13:49,009 --> 00:13:51,969
and help us live your
word tomorrow.

162
00:13:53,079 --> 00:13:56,098
In Jesus' name, amen.

163
00:13:59,888 --> 00:14:01,923
Right around the fence.

164
00:14:57,919 --> 00:15:00,956
That bus is as empty
as my grave.

165
00:15:00,958 --> 00:15:03,992
It starts to rain,
people get on that bus.

166
00:15:03,994 --> 00:15:06,628
No, they won't,
not unless they stupid as you are.

167
00:15:06,630 --> 00:15:11,567
Mama! If we can't ride the bus,
then do we have to go to school?

168
00:15:12,118 --> 00:15:14,429
Boy, you ain't never
took the bus in your life.

169
00:15:14,464 --> 00:15:16,606
Now get in there and help
me clean off that table.

170
00:15:25,017 --> 00:15:27,052
Hello, Mrs. Thompson?

171
00:15:27,054 --> 00:15:30,088
This is Odessa.

172
00:15:30,090 --> 00:15:33,491
Mrs. Thompson, I think I'm gonna
be awfully late to work today.

173
00:15:33,493 --> 00:15:38,063
Odessa, this is Monday. You know
how badly I need you on Monday.

174
00:15:38,065 --> 00:15:42,234
Yes, I know, Mrs. Thompson,
but, as I said, I...

175
00:15:42,236 --> 00:15:47,007
Well, this wouldn't have anything to do
with the boycott business, would it?

176
00:15:47,009 --> 00:15:51,411
Well, Mrs. Thompson, the buses usually
come past my house pretty near full,

177
00:15:51,413 --> 00:15:53,981
but today there ain't a soul
on 'em except the driver,

178
00:15:53,983 --> 00:15:56,084
and this last one had
a police car following it,

179
00:15:56,086 --> 00:16:00,646
- so, ma'am, I ain't likely to
ride the bus today. - Hmm.

180
00:16:01,359 --> 00:16:05,427
Well, I was goin' to Curb Market
this mornin' anyway.

181
00:16:05,429 --> 00:16:09,132
- You live down on Cobb Street,
don't you? - Yes, ma'am.

182
00:16:09,134 --> 00:16:11,554
Well, then I'll meet
you on the corner of

183
00:16:11,603 --> 00:16:13,808
Court and Mildred
in about an hour.

184
00:16:13,843 --> 00:16:16,105
- Thank you, ma'am.
- Okay. Bye-bye.

185
00:17:10,968 --> 00:17:13,887
Odessa, I'm not gonna be
able to carry you home.

186
00:17:13,922 --> 00:17:17,108
Mama needs help with Shelly's dinner,
so I'm gonna have to go over later.

187
00:17:17,110 --> 00:17:20,534
Yes, ma'am. Go and show your
mama how you're helpin'.

188
00:17:22,324 --> 00:17:24,027
Oh.
That's sweet.

189
00:17:48,743 --> 00:17:50,579
Good evening, ma'am.

190
00:18:05,332 --> 00:18:07,284
Whose turn is it
to do the dishes?

191
00:18:07,319 --> 00:18:08,731
- Theodore's.
- No, it ain't mine.

192
00:18:08,733 --> 00:18:11,569
- Well, who did 'em last night? - I did 'em.
It's Theodore and Franklin's turn.

193
00:18:11,571 --> 00:18:14,205
You got a choice: clean the
dishes or clean the outhouse.

194
00:18:14,473 --> 00:18:16,875
- Mama's home!
- Good. She can do the dishes.

195
00:18:17,354 --> 00:18:20,142
After you called, we waited
for you to come home, Mama.

196
00:18:20,177 --> 00:18:22,596
- We just ate while we waited.
- He's been waiting all night to say that.

197
00:18:22,631 --> 00:18:24,948
- Can I fetch you some supper? - Theodore
and Franklin keep makin' fun of my cookin',

198
00:18:24,983 --> 00:18:26,590
and Daddy won't
get them to stop.

199
00:18:26,625 --> 00:18:29,345
Still comin' to that mass meetin'?
It's in 15 minutes.

200
00:18:29,380 --> 00:18:31,697
- Selma, get your coat.
- What?

201
00:18:31,732 --> 00:18:34,594
Listen to a bunch of preachers talkin' 'bout
us plain folks wearin' out our shoes today

202
00:18:34,596 --> 00:18:36,883
while they drove around
in their cars?

203
00:18:36,918 --> 00:18:39,867
No, thank you. I put in my time at church
on Sunday morning, not Monday night.

204
00:18:39,869 --> 00:18:42,870
- Can I go, and Selma watch Franklin?
- I wanna go too!

205
00:18:42,872 --> 00:18:45,673
"I wanna go too!"

206
00:18:46,678 --> 00:18:49,119
Theodore gets to
have all the fun.

207
00:18:59,489 --> 00:19:03,294
- I think she cut up the cleanest
parts and fried it. - Shut up, fool.

208
00:19:03,633 --> 00:19:07,061
Mom, I'm sorry about supper.
I think it got worse as it got cold.

209
00:19:07,096 --> 00:19:10,634
Just let me get my shoes off.
I'll be ready in a minute.

210
00:19:10,636 --> 00:19:14,606
Mmm. I got to give that girl
some cookin' lessons.

211
00:19:15,422 --> 00:19:19,845
- Mama, your feet. - I just got to get
me some shoes that fit, that's all.

212
00:19:19,880 --> 00:19:22,393
I'll get up and change my dress.
I'll be ready in a minute.

213
00:19:24,342 --> 00:19:27,063
Don't wanna be late.
Might not get a seat.

214
00:19:27,388 --> 00:19:30,489
You quit that horsin' around
in my... Get off my bed!

215
00:19:32,360 --> 00:19:34,695
- Get in there.
- Daddy?

216
00:19:34,697 --> 00:19:37,532
You can't let her walk
down to the church.

217
00:19:37,534 --> 00:19:41,236
Don't worry about it.
It'll make her feel better to go.

218
00:19:41,238 --> 00:19:43,059
It really will.

219
00:19:49,351 --> 00:19:53,569
The only weapon that we have in our
hands this evening is the weapon of protest.

220
00:19:58,943 --> 00:20:00,926
And we are not wrong.

221
00:20:01,473 --> 00:20:04,613
We are not wrong
in what we are doing.

222
00:20:05,728 --> 00:20:09,913
If we are wrong, the supreme
court of this nation is wrong.

223
00:20:14,439 --> 00:20:16,675
If we are wrong,

224
00:20:16,677 --> 00:20:20,096
the Constitution of
the United States is wrong.

225
00:20:24,424 --> 00:20:27,977
If we are wrong,
God Almighty is wrong.

226
00:20:31,718 --> 00:20:36,798
